Question 1

Which command in SQL allows you to choose which columns will be returned in the result set?

  • GROUP BY
  • WHERE
  • SELECT
  • HAVING

The SELECT command is the first line of a standard SQL query and indicates which columns in the result set should be returned. WHERE is SQLâs filtering command. GROUP BY groups data by a single field to support aggregation, while HAVING is a secondary filter that can be used after a GROUP BY operation.

library(gghighlight)

  geom_bar(width=0.2 ) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits=c( "GROUP BY" ,"SELECT" ,  "HAVING" , "WHERE")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("SELECT"= "green" ) ,guide="none")

Question 4

An inner join between two tables returns

  • Only rows with a common identifier
  • All rows from one table, plus matching rows from the other
  • All rows in both tables

In general you only need to remember to kinds of joins - a âLEFT OUTER JOINâ and an âINNER JOINâ. Because all directional joins are âouterâ joins âLEFT JOINâ is shorthand for âLEFT OUTER JOINâ. An inner join returns only the rows that have a matching identifier in both tables, while a left join returns all rows from the left hand table (regardless of match), but only rows on the right where there is a match.

Question 6

What command would you use to calculate the number of days between two dates?

Date âadditionâ isnât well defined in standard SQL and is often handled differently by different databases (âlanguage extensionsâ)

All SQL databases should support simple subtraction such as âdate1 - date2â yielding a number of days.

Sometimes however we want our answer in a different way, and generally need a function

MS SQL Server has the command DATEDIFF which takes how you want the returned interval (hours, days, weeks etc) and two dates and returns the difference.

PostgresSQL which we will be using doesnât have a command like this, but it has something similar, the AGE() function. Instead of returning a number of days, it returns a special variable type called an interval. If we look at this as a string it will appear something like â1 year, 2 months and 3 daysâ, but underneath is really just an integer representing time in seconds. We can use a second function EXTRACT to pull out the portion we want, eg EXTRACT(DAYS FROM AGE(birthdate, deathdate))
